{
  "text": "Noise generated in the brain may influence brain behavior. Noise is generated in the brain by random spike firing times of neurons [CITATION_1] . By influencing the variability of the firing of neurons, noise may influence decision-making, memory, and the stability of short-term memory and attention [CITATION_2] . Furthermore, cognitive operations are also affected by stochasticity in N-methyl-D-aspartate activated receptors, which affect the stability of short-term memory and attention, and in alterations of gamma-amino-butyric acid receptor activated synaptic ion channel conductances which are predicted to influence how likely the system is to jump incorrectly into a pathological state of high activity [CITATION_3] . Similarly, in motor learning, the brain uses movement errors to adjust planning of future movements. This physiologically plausible strategy is optimally tuned to the properties of motor noise, and likely underlies learning in many motor tasks [CITATION_4] .",
